segments.text: I like to be selfish and say that I could never have learned this anywhere but Texas A&M.
Certainly that's not correct, but I think a person can get out of nearly anything that you do, say, or associate with about what you want to get out of it.
I would like to think that I could have gone to
most any school that offered the things that the Texas A&M did and gotten a basic background.
Here again, I'm not sure that I would have been as pleased with it as I was with A&M because I had an ingrained love for A&M.
I had been associated, lived near here, but I'm just not sure that all the things that
that I got there that I could have gotten just anywhere across the board.
I'm an Aggie at heart.
I just don't believe there's any place like it.
But here again, there are many fine places, and I've got to be.
Anything else that we missed that we should talk about?
No, I don't know of anything that we've missed, but I would like to just...

have pass a word to the succeeding people that come along and particularly I guess young military students and that is that many people that have gone on before us have as the saying goes have fought bled and died that that we could have what we've got and
I think that I could say to these young fellows, the way that you and I can pay our debt to the past is make the future indebted to us.
And I think so many times that people say, oh, you know, there's nothing worth working for anymore.
There's nothing worth fighting for anymore.
And that's not right.
I think we all have got a responsibility to take care of, and if we take care of it like the head of us did, we'll continue to be great.
And I have the greatest admiration for a bunch of young ROTC students that have chosen to take military training, and particularly now when it's

in in a few years past that was so unpopular yeah and i think uh i think that's a that's a feather in their head and i think that kind of person is going to be a good leader and i think they they'll say into the rest of the world you know this is this is important and regardless what you think about it i'm going to do it and i have an admiration for those people and i also think that
that the fact that it's voluntary is a feather in their hat.
And I also think that another thing that's made A&M great is the Corps of Cadets.
That has really been a stabilizing influence on that university over the years.
They've had some turmoils.
They've had some unrests and some demonstrations of tempted

and I think the Coral Cadets is to a great degree responsible for holding the boat steady and staying firm and staying strong and you know speaking out, showing up where they need to be, wearing the uniform.
I think that's another one of the reasons an Aggie is respected where he goes and he's
like he's looked up to.

And I think the fact that A&M University has provided more officers for the defense of this country than any other place, including West Point, is also another tribute to these fellows who have got all this ahead of them.
I think this is something for them to strive to keep up.
So I just say to them, you know,
Well, keep going.
Keep at it.
You've heard that saying about not asking a man if he's an Aggie, haven't you?
You know, you're not supposed to ask a man if he's an Aggie.
They say that you should not ask a fella if he's an Aggie, because if he isn't, she don't want to embarrass him, and if he is, he'll tell you soon enough.
Yeah, right.
That's not much of a note to end this thing on.
Well, this is a nice thought that you had about the Corps, and that's an excellent way, I think, on ending this very enjoyable interview that we've had.
Thank you very much, General Hanover.
I certainly appreciate it.
Well, I would say this to you, Terry.
I think it's a great undertaking that you have gotten into, and
Here again, this is voluntary.
Nobody told you to.
And I think it will pay tribute to some of us who have been more successful than others, whatever the reason.
And if the things that we have said or the ideas that we've portrayed can be of any significant use to anybody, I think your undertaking is certainly
pay off.
I know that you and this young lady are going to work on it or are going to put a lot of effort into it even though that's your job.
It's still a it's still a thing that I would hope a lot of people could have a lot of enjoyment out of and maybe get some ideas and I thank you.
Well thanks to the former students too.
Well that's right.
Support on us that was a great move on their part.
Thank you.
